# Image formats

Never use WebP on this site — it makes images look blurry.

## Who decides format

**The exporter decides JPG vs PNG in Figma.** The codebase does not classify assets.

- Save each file with the correct extension (`.jpg` or `.png`) in `public/images/`.
- `optimize-images.mjs` reads the extension and optimizes in that format — it never converts between JPG and PNG.
- Page code must reference the exact filename including extension.

## Format guidance (for export decisions)

| Asset type | Format |
|------------|--------|
| Photographs and photo-heavy composites (event photography, environmental shots, venue signage in situ) | **JPG** |
| Photorealistic 3D renders where imagery dominates (landscapes, spatial renders, volumetric models) | **JPG** |
| Logos, vectors, isometric/technical 3D views, wireframes, diagrams, text-first editorial layouts | **PNG** |

**Default to JPG when most of the frame is photographic or photorealistic**, even if the image includes some text — signage in a venue, a website on a device in context, a guide with photo backgrounds, or a render with incidental labels.

**Use PNG when text, UI, or flat graphics are the subject** — component specs, wireframes, floor plans, program grids, editorial layouts where legibility of type is critical, or anything needing crisp edges or transparency.

Logos need crisp edges and often transparency — export as PNG (e.g. `logo-*.png`).

**When unsure:** export a JPG, run `optimize-images.mjs`, and compare on the case-study page. Re-export as PNG only if small type or fine lines look unacceptable.

**Site examples (JPG):** `amnh-website`, `inpa-section-03-promotional-signage`, `cii-overview-signage`, `burton-render-spatial`.

**Site examples (PNG):** `amnh-affinity-map`, `inpa-section-05-editorial-layouts`, `verizon-section-02-widget-specifications`, `burton-plan-2d`.

## Figma export workflow

Use this for every project-page image added or re-exported from Figma.

### Exporter (manual)

1. **Find the image frame node** — the full-width frame in the page layout, not a thumbnail in a 3-up row.
2. **Export at 3200×1800** — fixed dimensions for all case-study images. Ensures 2× retina coverage at the ~1208px display width without upscaling.
3. **No border on export** — Figma frames have no stroke. The site adds a 1px `gray-20` border via CSS when pages pass `border: true` to `ProjectCaptionedImage`.
4. **Choose format and save** to `public/images/` with the project prefix (e.g. `amnh-affinity-map.png`, `amnh-website.jpg`). One file per basename — never leave both `.png` and `.jpg` for the same name.
5. **Run** `node scripts/optimize-images.mjs` — re-encodes each file **in place** (same extension; JPG quality 90; PNG compression level 9; max width 3200px for both). Updates blur placeholders in `src/data/image-assets.ts`. The script never converts PNG ↔ JPG. After a format swap, delete the old file manually or run with `--remove-stale-siblings`.
6. **Run** `node scripts/optimize-preview-images.mjs` when listing preview images change — writes `public/images/previews/` and `src/data/preview-image-assets.ts`.

### Agent (page build)

When the exporter has already placed images in `public/images/`:

1. Read text content, image order, captions, and layout (2-up groupings) from the Figma project page node.
2. Wire up the project page using exact filenames from `public/images/`.
3. Run `node scripts/optimize-images.mjs` after any new or replaced images.
4. Do **not** re-export from Figma MCP unless an image is missing or the exporter requests it.

### Source resolution

Blur means the **underlying pixels were low-res**, not that optimization failed. Before exporting, confirm image fills in Figma are ≥ 3200px wide. If a fill is smaller, replace it with a higher-res original in Figma first — exporting the frame at any scale only enlarges a soft source.

PNG vs JPG does not fix upscaling blur.

## Adding new assets

- Save with the correct `.jpg` or `.png` extension — that is all the optimize script needs.
- Do not add WebP conversion or `crop` fields in components.
- File paths in project pages must match filenames under `public/images/`.
- Do not update `PHOTO_BASENAMES` or any codebase format registry — that approach is retired.
